Ack

Please include detail on what the intent of this is.  "Converting dbus properties to redfish json in a declarative style" then pointing at the commit itself isn't very descriptive.  What are you trying to accomplish?  The best thing to do is to try to answer the "why".

Please find the design doc here https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/docs/+/63875
I have added cable.hpp as an example that covers dbus mapping and error handling use cases.
Please update the commit message to answer "why".  I've read your design doc, and I still don't understand.
added the reason for the utility in commit message
One key improvement might be lines of code, but this doesn't seem to significantly reduce the lines of code, which is part of the reason I'm confused.
suni

Welcome to the project.  Please familiarize yourself with the developing guides, both at project level and within the root of BMCWEB.  If you have any questions about the coding standards or rules, please ask them on discord or the mailing list BEFORE sending your patch, to avoid rework.

I stopped reviewing after 10 comments for things that are documented in the above.


Overall, reading through he code, this seems like it's proposing a significant change to how we write Redfish to DBus conversion handlers.  I love the experimental nature of this work and want to foster its development, so if you need any help in understanding the code, please don't hesitate to ask.

Please keep in mind that as a general rule, bmcweb aims for consistency in implementation, so any wide-sweeping changes would ideally need to come with accompanying patches to make at least a significant portion of the codebase consistent with any new philosophy, or prove that the efficiency of having two mechanisms for doing conversions is worth the added complexity.  Please work that into your plans for this feature.

Thanks Ed.
Please find the design doc here https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/docs/+/63875
Please don't use "using namespace".  It can cause collisions in the future that are hard to fix.  This is documented in cpp core guidelines.
Ack
Throwing in bmcweb results in a full crash, which I'm fairly certain wasn't your intent.
Ack
macros are disallowed in the coding standard and lint rules.
Ack
This method is disallowed by name in COMMON_ERRORS.md
May I know why? We have already made sure that "at" will be called after an exists check
What you're asking for is answered in the doc I pointed out above.  If you have questions, ask on discord or the mailing list.
Because of the danger of throwing to io_context and crashing all of bmcweb, exceptions in non-critical paths (like this parsing error) are disallowed.  Please rework your code to not use exceptions.
changed design to remove on_error handlers. No exception will be escaped from parser. All exception are converted in to error code

> No exception will be escaped from parser.

This statement has been made many times by many people.  I'm happy to discuss adding exceptions to non-critical paths, but not in the context of another very invasive change.

All of this patches error handling is for parsing errors, none of which are exceptional, therefore exceptions shouldn't be used.
Ack

I think it would help your effort considerably if you used a real example of an existing phosphor dbus interface here.  Dbus->redfish conversions are rarely 1:1, and copy/paste conversions are the only things you're showing here.
added an example port in changes to cable.hpp
Please do something like Processor or Sensor.  Cable is still far too simple.

1, wildcard captures are banned, because they cause lifetime problems.
2. please don't structure your callbacks with on_error/on_success handlers.  they prevent utilizing move-only objects in the captures (because both callbacks would need a copy of the capture.)
Ack
Please run your code through the formatter before pushing.  These kinds of violations are likely why your build failed.
Ack

As written, I'm not sure how this patchset helps.  It drops 10 lines in the cable example of IMO, relatively straightforward to read code (even if it includes loops), and replaces it with 700ish lines of very hard to read code, that, unless I'm mistaken, doesn't replicate the behavior of the old code faithfully.

I encourage you to keep working on refining the idea, and continue porting over more examples to try to get your idea to a net-negative line count, as well as simplify it, but as written, if this were deployed everywhere, I think it would hurt our debugability and readability.

This also adds about 2kB to the binary size for one conversion of one instance of a unpackPropertiesNoThrow call.  Assuming this scaling holds, there are 41 unpack properties calls;  41 * 2KB = 82KB, which means that if this patch is executed, it will add about 12% to the total binary size of bmcweb.  Please keep that in mind when making changes.

Isn't this basically the same as:

std::function<const DbusVariantType&,
              const sdbusplus::message::object_path&,
              std::string_view, std::string_view,
              MetaData&>
              
?
yes. But not as heavy as std::function. A quick protoype reveals the difference in assembly generation https://godbolt.org/z/WccnYvq56
Lets start with the simplest code, and we can optimize as it's appropriate.

I like to think I'm ok with c++, but code like this is really a lot tougher to read and understand.

also, this would be our first usage of concepts in the project that I'm aware of.  That's not to say you shouldn't, but lets make sure it actually reduces the complexity.

These concepts are used to pick proper overloads based on caller site usage. Most of them are very rare cases, but still needed to be added for complete support. This is similar to the crow::black_magic:: templates hidden behind BMCWEB_ROUTE. That reduces the caller site code a lot.

> These concepts are used to pick proper overloads based on caller site usage. Most of them are very rare cases, but still needed to be added for complete support. This is similar to the crow::black_magic:: templates hidden behind BMCWEB_ROUTE. That reduces the caller site code a lot.

You will notice that in the last year I've significantly reduced both the complexity and size of the black_magic namespace.  I would eventually like it to go away entirely, but for the moment it's down to 170 lines.  This code actively goes the other direction.

> That reduces the caller site code a lot.

This isn't true in a lot of cases, and just putting complexity outside of the call site doesn't solve the problem.  We need code that works, regardless of how many lines are written.
You've invented your own nlohmann::json::json_pointer type here.  Please don't invent your own, use what already exists, and we know escapes properly.
changed the implementation
Why are these objects special?  There's no way to map a unix_fd to a redfish output directly.

GenericNodeMapper specialization takes advantage of automatic conversion of types to nlohmann json. This avoids an explicit template arguments in mapToKey call. The types avoided here do not support such automatic conversion. But you can convert these types to Json by giving the template argument.

> GenericNodeMapper specialization takes advantage of automatic conversion of types to nlohmann json. This avoids an explicit template arguments in mapToKey call. The types avoided here do not support such automatic conversion. But you can convert these types to Json by giving the template argument.

That seems confusing as an API, but I think I understand now.
Like has been pointed out to you already, please don't use using namespace, per the coding standard.
Ack
I am struggling to see how this is easier code to write and maintain..

+1.  Yes, in this example it is 10 lines less code at the call site (21 lines instead of 32), but it:

A. Uses quite a few inline lambdas, that we know cause debugability problems (inline lambdas don't print very good call stacks) and review problems (clang format likes to changes them significantly on what should be trivial diffs).
B. Invokes a significant number of background lines (200 lines) of code that are harder to debug.
C. Instantiates multiple templates that are non-standard.

It depends on familiarity. If you read the code you will see that you are just stating the intent. "add a mapper that maps "CableTypeDescription" string property to "CableType" and report error if property missmatch. You will not write code for how to iterate the tree, how to unwrap the Dbus variant and how to report error. In trivial case(Majority) a one-liner will do the job. Look at the ethernet.hpp to see the 2 page long code do the same thing. The alternate solution that uses unpackPropertiesNoThrow may not scale well beyond 3 properties. Even in the simpler case such as this one the amount of code you write is still less. 
The template instantiation is upper-bounded by the number of different types in Dbus variant. But unpackPropertiesNoThrow instantiation depends on the number of possible permutations and combinations of the arguments.

Background code handles several other rare usages. Which will get instantiated only when we use it.

> It depends on familiarity. If you read the code you will see that you are just stating the intent. "add a mapper that maps "CableTypeDescription" string property to "CableType" and report error if property missmatch. 

With respect, I've read the code, and I definitely do not see the stated intent any more than I did in the previous code.  I see inline lambdas, which are disallowed, and callbacks that it's difficult to determine the effect of.

> You will not write code for how to iterate the tree, how to unwrap the Dbus variant and how to report error. In trivial case(Majority) a one-liner will do the job.

Please actually show this.  I do not see a case where the majority one liner would do the job.


> Look at the ethernet.hpp to see the 2 page long code do the same thing.

Ethernet was one of the first schemas written, and hasn't taken advantage of the latest helper functions.  Please start by moving ethernet over to the helper functions we already have before you do your comparison.

> The alternate solution that uses unpackPropertiesNoThrow may not scale well beyond 3 properties.

You say this.... but "may not scale well" does really tell me what the problem is.  Can you elaborate?  We have unpackPropertiesNoThrow calls that use more than 3 properties today.

> Even in the simpler case such as this one the amount of code you write is still less. 


Unless you count all the helper functions, in which case you've written more code, even if you assume we port over every handler, there will be more boilerplate.

> The template instantiation is upper-bounded by the number of different types in Dbus variant. But unpackPropertiesNoThrow instantiation depends on the number of possible permutations and combinations of the arguments.

I'm confused what argument you're making here.  If the argument that more code gets generated with unpackPropertiesNoThrow, that seems to be not true (the binaries on this patchset are larger).

> 
> Background code handles several other rare usages. Which will get instantiated only when we use it.

Quite confused at this statement.

This branch is also wrong.

the old behavior was

1. If it's finite: include it directly with no error.
2. if it's not finite, but nan, do not add it but do not put in an error.
3. if it's not finite, and not NAN, do not add it but add an error.

This patchset looks like it handles #2 incorrectly.
Ack , will update the code accordingly
Isn't this wrong?  This is going to return a filled std::optional with a default constructed double (ie 0.0), which would then get serialized as 0.0, not null right?
No. std::optional<double>() is null optional and will be evaluated to false in an if statement.
Right, which would mean that the property would get omitted from the json object rather than being put in as null?
This isn't the same has messages::internalError().
The internal error messages are already captured as part of the target Json. Here we are just setting the response code.
That seems error prone and confusing.  Is there any way to make that more clear?
Why?  Do licenses have some different way of managing dbus conversions compared to what we do today?

As-written, I still think the existing interfaces we have are better, and a change to the declarative style this patchset proposes would be a net negative on complexity, code review time, and readability.

Please continue to iterate it, and continue to make it:
A. In line with the coding standard (no inline lambdas, no exceptions in non-exceptional parsers, ect).
B. Show the improvement that is specified in the commit.  As-written, it's +700 lines of non-test code that frankly I have trouble reading, and gave up trying.  This is roughly quadruple compared to the black_magic namespace (170 lines) that it claims to be inspired by.
